{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_dill_ver02/data/sn91068695/00279559447/1945102501/0348.xml":{"full_text":"THE MARION PROGRESS\nPUBLISHED EVERY THURSDAY BY THE\nMcdowell publishing cq.\nMARION, N. C.\nTELEPHONE 64\nS. E. WHITTEN, Editor and Proprietor\nEntered at the Postoffice at Marion, N. C.,\nas second class matter.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATE:\nOne Year $1.50\nStrictly in Advance.\nSHOULD WORK TOGETHER\nOn of the difficulties that concerns the\nheathen, when they consider embracing Chris\ntianity, is the division that separated the var\nious churches. It is hard for a non-Christian\nto understand the exclusive claims and specific\ndoctrines of the various branches of Christian\nity. It is easy to understand the confusion\nthat befuddles the non-Christian thinker and\nto comprehend the logic of some non-Christians\nwho have expressed a willingness to become\nChristians but an unwillingness to become a\nmember of any particular branch of the Chris\ntian faith.\nWe do not believe that it is necessary for the\nvarious branches of Protestantism, or of the\nChristian faith, to become united into one\nchurch, but there is a great opportunity for\ncombined effort to convert non-believers, in\ncluding millions residing in the United States.\nIt should also be possible for the various church\norganizations to cooperate wholeheartedly in\nthe promotion of social and religious objectives\nin any nation which has established and main\ntains freedom of religious worship.\n\nSAVINGS ENORMOUS\nSavings by individuals in the United States,!\nduring the first six months of 1945, amounted j\nto $22,500,000,000, according to the Securities i\nand Exchange Commission, which reports that i\nliquid savings account for $18,600,000,000 of\nthe total.\n\"Analyzing what individuals saved during\nthe second quarter, the SEC says that they in\ncreased their holdings of Government securi\nties by $5,100,000,000, added $2,800,000,000\nto their cash and deposits, $1,500,000,000 to\ntheir equity in Government insurance, $1,000,\n000,000 to their equity in private insurance and\n$300,000,000 to their investments in savings\nand loan associations.\nThe figures reflect the unusual prosperity of\nthe first half of the present year and reveal that\nthe people of the country have, added consider\nably to the huge backlog of spending power\nwhich they amassed earlier.\nThe existence of such a large volume of\nliquid savings, which means that they can be\ncashed and expended, adds to the general in\nflationary threat which now hovers over the\nnation. If turned loose in a precipated de\nmand for goods, the huge savings would lead\nto a disstressing situation.\nNAVY DAY\nSaturday, October 27, is Navy Day.\nTo the gallant men and women in the United\nStates Navy from the days of the Revolution\nthrough World War II, America doffs its hat.\nIt was during the Revolution that the need\nfor a Navy became evident to the patriots. The\nBritish at Boston could not be defeated because\nthey were getting supplies from British ships\nwhich sailed into the harbor.\nTo cut off these supplies, some worthy New\nEngland seaman, backed by Connecticut and\nRhode Iisland, sailed out in small vessels to\ncapture or destroy the British ships. They suc\nceeded so well that Congress organized a Nav\nal Committee with John Adams at its head to\norganize American vessels. The Americans\nwith their 64 vessels captured 196 British ves\nsels worth about six million dollars during the\nwar and also obtained war materials without\nwhich the country could not have won.\nIt is to the Navy, fellow Americans, that we\nowe much of our freedom. Salute to the gobs!\nLet's not worry about Army, Navy or Air\nForce; this nation is rich enough to have all\nthree in ample proportions for complete pro\ntection.\nDon't forget the War Bond drive that will\nsoon invite Americans to celebrate thneir victory\nin a way that means something.\nAdvertisers, anxious for full value, should\nunderstand that the basis of price is quality cir\nculation in great quantity.\nIt is always intelligent to look ahead and to\nplan ahead.\nA TIME FOR THOUGHT, NOT FEARS\nAny change-over of such magnitude as the\nreconversion we are now going through is\nbound to require time and to cause some un\ncertainties. This stage of it calls'for steady\nthinking instead of groundless fears. For that\nreason Country Gentleman asked two men,\nwhose views it has learnd to respect, how the\noutlook appeared to them. One is a hard\nminded Government economist and the other is\na forecaster for a large corporation, with a\nhigh record of accuracy. _ They are in fairly\nclose accord as to the outlook.\nBoth look for the sag that started at the war's\nend to carry general activity and national in\njcomes to possibly fifteen per Cent below recent\nI wartime levels. The Government man figures\n!conditions should firm up by March first; the\nindustrial forecaster thinks this may come by\nJanuary. Both expect an active rate of re\nconversion operations by July first, with the\n'.country entering what may become a boom\n:j period by the end of 1946. Both feel that any\ni widespread unemployment will be temporary\n'and should recede rapidly once reconversion\njgets into full swing. A farm income around\ni 1941-42 levels is indicated.\nI The basic factors in the situation bear out I\n\nithis conclusion. No excess supplies of raw,\nmaterials are pressing on the market, as after\nthe previous war. Prices have not been per- j\nmitted to rise to levels where disastrous breaks\nwould be inevitable. There is no such vulner- j\nable situation as when the Federal Reserve, af-1\nI\nter the other war, called on country banks for\nthe repayment of loans and set the whole farm j\nand ranch debt structure toppling. Country I\nbanks now have more cash and deposits than\nthey know how to use, and farm debts are low\nier than when the war began. Consumer in\njdebtedness also is down, thanks to the curbs on\n(installment buying. Savings of the American,\npeople, in fact, are at an all-time peak. j\nMore people want more things and have\nmore money to buy them with than ever before.\njThe productive capacity to satisfy these unfill-1\nJ ed wants is the largest in our history. The task\nis simply one of seeing the intervening period\nthrough until all these favorable factors are in j\ngear. It may mean some hard going for a!\nwhile, but the outcome should be in no doubt.\nIf we must fear anything let's fear the right I1\nthing. The question is not are we going to,\nhave good times, but whether they will get out i,\nof hand and develop into a boom and bust.\u2014 'i\nCountry Gentleman. i\nWOODLAND HARVEST\nA man goes to the woods these days\u2014as\nhe ought. He goes to gather autumn's harvest.\nHe gleans it from atop a mossy boulder or by\nscuffing through leaf-strewn woodland paths, j\nHe watches the flaming maples as they sweep j\nacross the sky, or the birch and beechnut preen\ning brown and yellow leaves in a gentle breeze, j\nHe closes his eyes and cocks an ear to the\nchuckle of a tiny stream as it swaps jokes with\na speckled trout. He hears a chipmunk scold\na gray squirrel for stealing a choice nut. He\nlistens to the winter song of the chickadee or\nthe wind strumming the Aeolian harp of the\npines.\nStrolling along the wooded trails he follows\nthe beaten bath of a rabbit or stops to examine\nan autumn flower. And, as he goes, he picks\na bouquet of colored leaves brightened with a\nsprig of goldenrod and a cluster of berries\u2014\nand, of course, he'll fill it out with a variety of\nasters. Then, those hickorynuts or butternuts\nor chestnuts\u2014his foraging wouldn't be com\nplete until he had stuffed his pockets with\nthem.\nThere's a harvest in the.woods, these days, a\nman discovers.\u2014Christian Science Monitor.\nThe Progress is always glad to receive con\ntributed news items from authentic sources; it\nis especially anxious to receive data about re\nturning soldiers, sailors and other service folks.\nIf you know of someone who has come home,\nwithout proper publicity, make it your business j\nto send us the facts. j\nEvery municipality, including Marion, would\nbe surprised to discover how much can be ac*\ncomplished by community cooperation and un\nselfish leadership.\nLet us hope that there will not be another\nwar but let us be sure that if it conies the na\n:ion will be prepared to defend itself by proper\noffensive strategy.\nWe strongly advise every returning veteran\n;o take advantage of whatever educational op\nportunity that is available.\nIf inflation hits the nation in full force the\nsavings of every citizen will become less val\nuable.\nOur own prediction is that the country will\nsoon be overrun by salesmen.\nPeace, to last, must be satisfactory to all\nnations.\nThe Everyday\nCounselor\nBy Rev. Herbert Spaugh, D. D.\nWhile Dr. Spaugh is on vacation\nhis place will be taken today by\nBishop J. Kenneth Pfahl of the Sou\nthern Moravian (Episcopal) Church\nWinston-Salem, N. C.\nI have just finished reading\n\"When the Soul Goes, Man Goes,\"\nby Dorothy Thompson, in the cur\nrent Ladies Home Journal. Yes, 1\nread it the second time and found\nit most rewarding. It evidences\nkeen intellectual discernment and\ndre e p spiritual illumination. Of\ncourse, I give it a strictly Christian\ninterpretation. Moreso, perhaps,\nthan the writer might wish to do.\nAnd in so doing I find my faith\nstrongly buttressed by undeniable\nfacts. It has underscored for me\nthe unforgettable fashion the words\nof Isaiah 26:9, \"When the judgment\nof God are in the earth, the inhabi\ntants of the earth will learn right\neousness.\"\nAgain, it calls to mind the words\nof Jesus, Matthew 16:26, \"What is\na man profited, if he gain the whole\nworld and lose his own soul? Or\nwhat shall a man give in exchange\nfor his soul?\" How foolish the\nGerman nation has been. And, per\nhaps, there are other nations which\nneed to be warned ere it is too late.\nWar is a cruel and expensive\nteacher, yet who will say it is not\na good one? And, if men and na\ntions in stubborn self-will and pride\nrefuse other provisions which God\nhas made for their instruction, may\nit not be one of the ways by which i\n'He maketh the wrath of man to j\npraise Him?\"\nWhat a sermon is contained in\n;hose last paragraphs! in our judg- j\nnent few greater lessons have come i\n;o us out of all that has been writ-1\n;en about the war. We quote them\n;o give them wider publicity:\n\"The lesson of Dachau is that no j\nicience, not technology, no politi-!\n:al, social or economic systems,\nleither patriotism nor race, nor\nmaterial standards of living, nor\nlearning, nor civilization will save\nmankind from relapse into the most\nmonstrous savagery, but only the\nmost careful nurture of his noblest\ninstincts.\nj \"I asked an old friend who serv\n'ed twenty months in the dreadful\ndeath house of Tauthausen,. issuing\nfrom its half mummy and half man,;\n/Who behaved best among the in-J\nmates? Businessmen? Intellectuals?\nWhat race? What political part- j\nies?' j\n\"He answered, after thinking a\nlong time, 'Pritests.'\n\"I shall remember that answer\nforever, and translate it into a larg- i\ner generalization: They remained j\nmen, in conditions of lowest beast- j\niality, who served an Image and an j\nIdeal higher than the highest ach- j\nievements of man; an Ideal in whom\nalone man attains significance and j\nworth. They were those who knew j\nthat man, as man, is a soul.\"\nj\nI wish the writer had written j\n\"God\" instead of \"Image\" and j\n\"Christ\" instead of \"Ideal.\" It was\nher article, however; but how re-j\nvealing of the basic truth as to what1\nhas happened. How illuminating\nfor the course which is ahead of us,\nin the rebuilding of life by individ-1\nuals and nations! Not only must j\nthe \"soul,\" the spiritual in man, not i\nbe forgotten, it must be given first\nplace. Otherwise disaster.\nAnd what endorsement we have\nfor the Book of Books! Surely the\nBible scores again! It is the great\ntext book of life for the individual 1\nHEADACHE\nCapudine quickly eases\nheadache and lootheg result\ning upset nerves because it's\nliquid\u2014nothing to dissolve.\nUse only as directed.\nLiquid CAPUDINE\nend for nations. It is an unfailing\nguide, \"a lamp to our feet, a light\nto our path.\" Let Christians turn\nanew to the Look with confidence\na .id cpura\u00a33. Let it be taught to\nour children. Let it find its rightful\nplace in the business office and :n\nthe councils of the nations. Let its\nlessons nnd precepts by the plumb\nline by which we build the era of\npeace.\nOnly six states in the U. S. show\nan increase in egg production for\nthe first 9 months of 1945 as com\npared with last year. North Caro\nlina leads the league in gains.\nThe steam turbine works on the\nsame principle as the windmill.\nWhy Mary\u2014\nMy Cough Is Gone!\n\"Bronchuline Sure Acts With Speed!\nNow I Know I Can Get Some Sleep.\"\nSuch Can represent the surprising\nexperience of thousands who try\nBRONCHULINE for the first time!\nTou positively cannot buy anything1\nbetter for common racking coughs,\nBronchial Coughs and Throat Irri\ntation due to colds. At once you\nfeel its warming effects starting to\nwork everywhere inside your throat,\nthen the comforting easing! Medi\nr cines of such amazing efficiency\ncommand the highest respect of all!\nTry BRONCHULINE just ONCH\nfor coughs due to colds and we are\nconfident your homo will never be\nwithout It,\nHARRISONS DRUG STORE\nA MARION MAN FELT\nLIKE SWOLLEN BALLOON;\nFULL OF STOMACH GAS\nRecently, a Marion man stated\nthat he used to feel like a swollen\nballoon after every meal. He would\nbloat full of gas and spit up acidu\nlous liquids for hours after eating.\nWas terribly constipated. This man\nis one of the hundreds in this vic\ninity who now praise INNER-AID.\nHe states he w'as amazed at the re\nsults when he took this medicine.\nNow he eats what he wants with\nout gas or bloating, and bowels are\nregular for the first time in years.\nHe feels like a new man.\nINNER-AID contains 12 Great\nHerbs; they cleanse bowels, clear\ngas from stomach, act on sluggish\nliver and kidneys. Miserable peo\nple soon feel different all over. So\nion't go on suffering! Get INNER\nAID. Sold by all Drug Stores her^\nn McDowell County.\nThe Future of Pulpwood in\nNORTH CAROLINA\nOne result of the war has been to\nmake the people of this state more\nconscious than ever before of the\ngreat asset we have in our pulpwood\nresources.\nNow that complete victory has\nbeen won, the new usefulness of\npulpwood will result in increased\npeacetime consumption of paper,\nrayon, plastics and many other prod\nucts of pulpwood. Part of our vast\nforest heritage, pulpwood \u2014a basic\nAmerican industry\u2014will continue to\nserve the nation in peace, as it did\nin war.\nMake the Most of this Asset\nIntelligent cutting of pulpwood pays\nbig dividends. By adequate planting\nand selective cutting even a small\nfarm woodland can yield a valuable\ncrop of pulpwood periodically. It\nis a crop which needs only a little\ncare and can be harvested at any\nconvenient time. It is another cash\ncrop. Consult your nearest district\nforester.\n14J, K. BeicJtle*\nState Forester\nPROPER THINNING MAKES TREES\nAFTfir\nTHINNING\"\nPREVENT FOREST FIRES\nFires kill trees for present and\nfuture needs and make land un\nproductive. Everybody loses and\nnobody profits when forests burn.\nBe sure fires are out!\nVICTORY PULPWOOD COMMITTEE\nS. L. HOMEWOOD, Chairmaw\nW. S. HAYNES, Rt. 2, Marions\nC. Y. PYATT, Nebo.\nJ. E. ENGLISH, Asbford.\nCECIL MOODY, Old Fort\nVICTORY\nl>\nEEZE33\nWI'li/lH'li","height":"31488","width":"21052"}}
